00:07:26,987 --> 00:07:28,588
It's a true Cinderella story.

137
00:07:28,928 --> 00:07:30,008
So it's fun to talk about it.

138
00:07:30,068 --> 00:07:32,709
And it's fun to talk about how this group of creatives

139
00:07:33,949 --> 00:07:35,390
somehow found each other on this.

140
00:07:36,070 --> 00:07:42,674
tiny but huge planet and made Ori and the forest, in the Blind Forest. It's quite remarkable and it was an amazing

141
00:07:43,135 --> 00:07:56,744
opportunity to be a part of. So let's jump into it. So, you know, in kind of common lexicon, Moon Studios is a flat

142
00:07:56,804 --> 00:08:03,508
organization, much like you may have read about Valve. However, the focus is on the

143
00:08:05,149 --> 00:08:07,110
was very strong about what we were doing.

144
00:08:07,771 --> 00:08:11,913
And so I just want to kind of give a little bit of like where the ground rules were

145
00:08:11,933 --> 00:08:12,754
and what was

146
00:08:13,114 --> 00:08:14,535
what was flexing and what wasn't.

147
00:08:15,475 --> 00:08:16,016
This game

148
00:08:17,516 --> 00:08:20,398
from our founders was going to be

149
00:08:21,058 --> 00:08:23,580
a beautiful, very tight, metrovania platformer.

150
00:08:24,420 --> 00:08:28,383
We knew exactly that that's what we were doing. It was hammered home all the time.

151
00:08:32,005 --> 00:08:35,106
We knew, which I think is very important, why we were making it.

152
00:08:35,666 --> 00:08:40,367
And that is for the hardcore fans of the classic 2D platformer.

153
00:08:40,547 --> 00:08:42,567
We knew if we could satisfy that crowd,

154
00:08:43,127 --> 00:08:46,308
make it as pretty as we knew we could sonically and visually,

155
00:08:46,668 --> 00:08:47,528
we would be OK.

156
00:08:47,948 --> 00:08:49,248
Now that doesn't mean it's easy to do,

157
00:08:49,488 --> 00:08:54,149
but this was the ground rules.

158
00:08:54,189 --> 00:08:56,590
Day one on the project, this is what was presented to me.

159
00:08:56,650 --> 00:08:57,770
This is what we're doing.

160
00:08:59,370 --> 00:08:59,690
However.

161
00:09:01,317 --> 00:09:09,419
how we're making it, outside of it being chosen that it is being done in Unity, it's a battle.

162
00:09:09,499 --> 00:09:12,980
And everybody in this room probably feels that, yeah, of course, that's kind of why

163
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:13,420
we're here.

164
00:09:13,500 --> 00:09:18,321
We like doing game design because we're figuring out how to give new experiences, even when

165
00:09:18,341 --> 00:09:24,003
we're wrapping a new experience around a classic type platform, like a 2D platformer.

166
00:09:25,481 --> 00:09:28,963
So, let's dig deeper into what makes Moon special.

167
00:09:29,583 --> 00:09:31,144
And as the concept of ownership...

168
00:09:32,325 --> 00:09:34,166
Sorry, here, let me get one more point in here.

169
00:09:35,546 --> 00:09:40,689
In a flat organization, this is, I think, probably ubiquitous with most flat organizations,

170
00:09:40,769 --> 00:09:42,710
is that you remove a management layer,

171
00:09:42,730 --> 00:09:45,271
so you have zero management, but...

172
00:09:46,407 --> 00:09:49,350
The management falls back on every individual in the organization.

173
00:09:49,430 --> 00:09:53,434
It's only going to succeed if everybody in there is managing their resources,

174
00:09:54,355 --> 00:09:56,577
whether it be individually or through group dynamics,

175
00:09:56,717 --> 00:09:57,998
to the betterment of the project.

176
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:02,903
So, it's an everybody-is-managing-when-nobody-is-managing kind of idea.

177
00:10:05,067 --> 00:10:09,630
Now, to the point where I think Moon is very, very different, or at least the first time

178
00:10:09,690 --> 00:10:19,177
I had ever worked in this type of environment, was that Moon has a culture of rapid iteration,

179
00:10:19,517 --> 00:10:24,821
and everybody who's capable and available and has a legitimate amount of interest is

180
00:10:24,881 --> 00:10:27,203
expected to review everything.

181
00:10:29,675 --> 00:10:36,501
What you come up with, as Gareth alluded to, is we did this entire project basically in Skype through chat channels like this.

182
00:10:36,881 --> 00:10:42,687
And if you see that circle there on the left-hand side where it says moon and it says 2135, that might be about an hour's worth of messages.

183
00:10:49,590 --> 00:10:54,196
because there is constant feedback, there's constant discussion.

184
00:10:54,977 --> 00:10:57,941
Skype was our big water cooler, if you will,

185
00:10:58,802 --> 00:11:03,288
that was constantly going the entire time we were developing the project.

186
00:11:04,689 --> 00:11:08,492
So what does that really look like for a sound designer or a composer?

187
00:11:09,352 --> 00:11:14,075
I think it varied a little bit between us, just based on the levels of granularity that

188
00:11:14,115 --> 00:11:17,017
we're kind of individually going into the engine and designing.

189
00:11:18,458 --> 00:11:23,180
But sorry, let me skip around a tiny, tiny bit.

190
00:11:26,711 --> 00:11:27,372
What does that mean?

191
00:11:27,412 --> 00:11:29,354
Let me just quickly go back to this one.

192
00:11:29,714 --> 00:11:33,698
If I'm creating a sound, and I feel like it's important

193
00:11:33,778 --> 00:11:36,721
that somebody would want to hear it and make a judgment call

194
00:11:36,781 --> 00:11:40,705
on it, like an attack or a UI sound or something

195
00:11:40,725 --> 00:11:42,967
that I think is relatively important.

196
00:11:43,627 --> 00:11:47,569
throw it in the game, you know, obviously make, you know, do my, do my best shot at

197
00:11:47,589 --> 00:11:52,231
it, throw it in the game, alert the team, whoever's online, if they're not doing anything

198
00:11:52,271 --> 00:11:56,272
crushing that they just absolutely have to get done, they're going to take a listen and

199
00:11:56,292 --> 00:11:56,893
give feedback.

200
00:11:57,173 --> 00:12:00,614
And when I say somebody, it could be a QA tester, it could be the creative director,

201
00:12:02,115 --> 00:12:03,195
all the way up and down the line.

202
00:12:03,835 --> 00:12:05,436
It's important to remember that this goes both ways.

203
00:12:05,476 --> 00:12:09,438
It's not just for the, it's not just the audio when we put stuff in, it's like, so when artists

204
00:12:09,458 --> 00:12:12,599
put in stuff and I don't like it, okay.

205
00:12:13,068 --> 00:12:15,590
Composer doesn't like the art in one part of the game.

206
00:12:16,351 --> 00:12:17,992
It's unprecedented, it's not normal,

207
00:12:18,233 --> 00:12:22,076
but when it's consistent across the entire organization

208
00:12:22,797 --> 00:12:26,240
and you get used to it, then it can work.

209
00:12:26,858 --> 00:12:30,719
Yeah, and I'll give a quick example too, just to try it on that, because I think it's a really cool point.

210
00:12:31,280 --> 00:12:41,704
And we're going to get into more examples as well, but there was a visual effect put on into the game very, very, very, very late in the first ten minutes of playing it.

211
00:12:42,064 --> 00:12:45,785
And if you guys have played the game, it's very mood setting, it's got what it's going on.

212
00:12:46,285 --> 00:12:54,108
And this effect was done for something else. It was a global effect that came in, and it really ruined the mood of the scene.

213
00:12:54,649 --> 00:12:57,790
And I made a squawk about it, and it got out.

214
00:12:57,811 --> 00:13:00,152
So I'm just showing you, and we've gotten better examples here.

215
00:13:00,232 --> 00:13:04,755
But just through the process of group dynamics,

216
00:13:05,115 --> 00:13:06,396
other people were able to agree with that.

217
00:13:06,556 --> 00:13:09,498
We got some kind of inertia around, yeah, this really is affecting

218
00:13:09,558 --> 00:13:11,199
the way the mood of this place is going.

219
00:13:11,219 --> 00:13:14,420
You know, on the sound design side, I would have had to really amp up

220
00:13:14,461 --> 00:13:18,363
the effects to get that to look proper, and it was going to ruin

221
00:13:18,403 --> 00:13:22,065
both sonically and visually, I felt, the mood of that area.

222
00:13:22,746 --> 00:13:29,550
So, making that work, you know, as a developer or as if you're kind of in charge of bringing

223
00:13:29,590 --> 00:13:32,792
people into the team, you obviously got to look for competent, talented people.

224
00:13:32,832 --> 00:13:34,313
That's true of any organization.

225
00:13:34,634 --> 00:13:40,177
You also have to find people who can champion their own causes and are self-motivated.

226
00:13:40,798 --> 00:13:42,339
You do not get a to-do list.

227
00:13:42,379 --> 00:13:46,021
There is not, you know, for the most part, a bug tracking system or a task list.

228
00:13:46,041 --> 00:13:47,322
We don't do agile development.

229
00:13:47,602 --> 00:13:50,363
Like, there's not really a structure around this.

230
00:13:51,204 --> 00:13:53,604
It is a very organic process.

231
00:13:54,085 --> 00:13:56,165
You gotta have some thick skin.

232
00:13:56,245 --> 00:14:01,007
Keep in mind this is a multinational team.

233
00:14:01,507 --> 00:14:03,048
Not everybody speaks the same language.

234
00:14:03,188 --> 00:14:07,089
Not everybody has the same cultural mores.

235
00:14:07,149 --> 00:14:09,690
You're a global citizen when you're working on a project like this.

