I might have stumbled upon it.

704
00:46:18,202 --> 00:46:21,324
But I had access to the game from so early.

705
00:46:21,365 --> 00:46:23,146
So I was able to try out so many things.

706
00:46:23,166 --> 00:46:25,008
Like, what feels like good platform music?

707
00:46:25,068 --> 00:46:27,810
I've got to add, like, this is not like my thing,

708
00:46:27,970 --> 00:46:29,872
this is the only way to score a platformer.

709
00:46:30,072 --> 00:46:31,593
But this, I feel like, is the only way

710
00:46:31,633 --> 00:46:32,534
I could have scored Ori.

711
00:46:32,994 --> 00:46:34,255
And I think.

712
00:46:35,296 --> 00:46:39,280
Without the experimentation process at the beginning, I'm not sure I would have arrived at this,

713
00:46:39,340 --> 00:46:44,965
because this pulse and sustained tones combination was the result of hours and hours of play testing.

714
00:46:44,985 --> 00:46:49,710
And I'll add to the huge, huge, huge, enormous thank you, Gareth, advantage to...

715
00:46:50,991 --> 00:47:00,253
the sound design was that Ori is a pretty interesting piece of material, material spirit

716
00:47:00,593 --> 00:47:09,994
in an organic field, in a real life environment. So without, with him using so much restraint

717
00:47:10,034 --> 00:47:14,835
in the music example, not using so much percussion, it gave so much more space to be able to hear

718
00:47:14,855 --> 00:47:18,736
Ori sliding down a wood tree or walking on rocks.

719
00:47:19,556 --> 00:47:23,860
which you then feel. It transports you into that. It makes you feel like you're a part of that.

720
00:47:23,900 --> 00:47:26,682
It's back to that micro, macro thing. It draws you in.

721
00:47:26,843 --> 00:47:31,467
Exactly. Yet the Brilliant score is still giving you everything you need emotionally, pulse-wise.

722
00:47:31,987 --> 00:47:36,851
It's, I think it's a huge key as to how that synergy wrapped, intertwined.

723
00:47:37,632 --> 00:47:40,335
So the last thing I wanted to talk about was our cutscene approach.

724
00:47:40,655 --> 00:47:40,795
So

725
00:47:42,824 --> 00:47:46,566
Normally, there's a lot of ways, I guess there's a few ways you can approach cutscenes.

726
00:47:46,606 --> 00:47:51,009
The worst way is you get handed a video by the developer and it comes with temp music

727
00:47:51,129 --> 00:47:52,230
and hey, rip off the temp.

728
00:47:52,630 --> 00:47:54,632
That's not very satisfying, please don't do that.

729
00:47:56,013 --> 00:48:01,136
The next is you get a cutscene and maybe there's no music, that's okay.

730
00:48:01,817 --> 00:48:02,738
So on Ori...

731
00:48:04,006 --> 00:48:07,028
We had storyboards, and the storyboards were given to me,

732
00:48:07,448 --> 00:48:11,031
and I was able to extend or shorten the storyboards,

733
00:48:11,631 --> 00:48:16,414
so in order, and, so I could make a piece of music

734
00:48:16,794 --> 00:48:18,716
that had a nice flow and arc.

735
00:48:19,856 --> 00:48:22,838
This helped define exactly what the cutscenes are.

736
00:48:24,577 --> 00:48:28,960
And we're going to show an example of one of the cut scenes, where I took different approaches.

737
00:48:29,760 --> 00:48:34,484
And this is an example of where the music actually would have influenced the art.

738
00:48:35,524 --> 00:48:40,368
Because the music ended up being done for the cut scenes first, and then the cut scenes got made.

739
00:48:41,068 --> 00:48:43,970
And if we'd gone in one direction, the art would have been quite different.

740
00:48:44,050 --> 00:48:46,792
So here is a cut scene where...

741
00:48:47,893 --> 00:48:50,796
Kuro, the antagonist, is facing off against Ori.

742
00:48:50,836 --> 00:48:54,260
It's one of the first times they meet each other in the game and here's the first approach

743
00:48:54,300 --> 00:48:55,161
that I took.

744
00:48:59,045 --> 00:49:01,788
This is what concepting looks like by the way.

745
00:49:34,189 --> 00:49:35,313
Right, that's like one approach.

746
00:49:36,016 --> 00:49:37,601
It's pretty clear that's the villain, right?

747
00:49:41,914 --> 00:49:44,255
And Thomas, our director, saw that and was like,

748
00:49:44,875 --> 00:49:47,796
this is really good, but it's the wrong message to send out.

749
00:49:48,316 --> 00:49:51,297
And if that scene had been developed by artists,

750
00:49:51,377 --> 00:49:53,958
and it takes a lot of work to do the art for the game,

751
00:49:53,978 --> 00:49:55,419
and it would have been a lot of wasted work

752
00:49:55,459 --> 00:49:56,439
if we'd gone with that direction,

753
00:49:56,459 --> 00:49:58,000
because we ultimately didn't go in that direction.

754
00:49:58,460 --> 00:50:00,801
It's very dark, and the art creator for the scene

755
00:50:01,021 --> 00:50:04,382
would have had that dark feel in mind.

756
00:50:04,882 --> 00:50:06,863
So here's the mock-up for the second approach.

757
00:50:40,924 --> 00:50:44,085
Now it's less obvious that Kuro is the villain.

758
00:50:44,105 --> 00:50:47,586
There's obviously it's still a big moment and it's still quite scary but it's not like

759
00:50:47,786 --> 00:50:49,827
it's not blindingly obvious anymore.

760
00:50:50,567 --> 00:50:53,808
Our villain is misunderstood and this is the first time we want to tell the player that's

761
00:50:53,848 --> 00:50:55,489
like it's yes Kuro is.

762
00:50:56,489 --> 00:50:59,512
Kira is your antagonist, but there's a little bit more to it than that.

763
00:51:00,372 --> 00:51:06,938
And then what happens is the art gets put on top on the final cut scene and it makes

764
00:51:06,978 --> 00:51:08,219
it easy for the artist to get in.

765
00:51:08,779 --> 00:51:10,661
I hope they were inspired by the music.

766
00:51:11,481 --> 00:51:14,724
And I think if we'd gone in the first direction, the scene would look a lot different than

767
00:51:14,744 --> 00:51:15,184
it is now.

768
00:51:15,244 --> 00:51:19,367
It's still a little bit scary, but it's not all black and white and silhouetty.

769
00:51:19,568 --> 00:51:20,428
It's just a lot of blue.

770
00:51:20,448 --> 00:51:25,212
So here's the final with the recorded orchestra and everything put together.

771
00:52:04,509 --> 00:52:05,350
All right, I'm just there.

772
00:52:05,931 --> 00:52:06,231
OK.

773
00:52:06,692 --> 00:52:09,256
So what I learned in this process,

774
00:52:09,296 --> 00:52:11,560
and you're going to get my big message today,

775
00:52:12,702 --> 00:52:15,266
the composer can and should be testing for things

776
00:52:15,306 --> 00:52:17,009
that regular QA testing cannot.

777
00:52:17,570 --> 00:52:17,710
So.

778
00:52:19,328 --> 00:52:23,329
And especially in a small team, you've got no one really,

779
00:52:23,429 --> 00:52:25,490
you've got people testing for audio, but they're testing for like,

780
00:52:26,110 --> 00:52:26,850
does the loop work?

781
00:52:27,451 --> 00:52:28,431
There's no audio here.

782
00:52:29,251 --> 00:52:30,152
Why is there a glitch here?

783
00:52:30,512 --> 00:52:34,473
But who is testing the emotional flow from level one

784
00:52:35,093 --> 00:52:35,814
all the way to the end?

785
00:52:35,974 --> 00:52:37,054
Who's responsible for that?

786
00:52:37,474 --> 00:52:39,175
The composer is responsible for that.

787
00:52:39,515 --> 00:52:42,316
And really, that's your number one responsibility.

788
00:52:42,336 --> 00:52:45,897
And the only way, the only possible way you are going to find that out

789
00:52:45,917 --> 00:52:47,778
is if you play the game you're working on.

790
00:52:48,278 --> 00:52:50,120
And yes, it requires a lot of hours.

791
00:52:50,280 --> 00:52:51,501
I spent so many hours.

792
00:52:51,781 --> 00:52:57,687
And I, you know, I didn't invoice Moon, please pay me extra money for playing your game for

793
00:52:57,928 --> 00:52:58,428
500 hours.

794
00:52:58,909 --> 00:52:59,829
But it's part of your job.

795
00:52:59,849 --> 00:53:00,670
You've got to play the game.

796
00:53:00,931 --> 00:53:05,135
And if you don't have time or if you're bad at games, go to, go find a student who is

797
00:53:05,195 --> 00:53:08,018
into games and they'll probably be really happy to play games for you.

798
00:53:09,379 --> 00:53:09,499
So.

799
00:53:10,360 --> 00:53:13,443
The big thing is you've got to play the game you're working on.

800
00:53:13,743 --> 00:53:18,168
Now, don't get me wrong, there are examples, hundreds of examples, of amazing scores, I'm

801
00:53:18,228 --> 00:53:19,850
sure, where the composer didn't play the game.

802
00:53:20,230 --> 00:53:27,097
But my feeling is that you will get your best effort, the developer will get your best effort

803
00:53:27,237 --> 00:53:32,342
if you are playing the game actively and looking at the grand emotional experience from A to

804
00:53:32,362 --> 00:53:32,382
B.

805
00:53:32,863 --> 00:53:34,944
If you're doing a film, you would sit with the director

806
00:53:35,064 --> 00:53:36,785
and do lots of playbacks with the director,

807
00:53:36,965 --> 00:53:38,446
and they would tell you what they like and didn't like.

808
00:53:38,566 --> 00:53:39,786
It should be the same for games.

809
00:53:40,166 --> 00:53:41,747
I know I'm pretty sure that it isn't,

810
00:53:41,767 --> 00:53:43,468
and it's something I feel really strongly about.

811
00:53:43,888 --> 00:53:45,909
All composers in the room, please play your games.

812
00:53:46,269 --> 00:53:48,611
And all devs in the room, please encourage,

813
00:53:48,931 --> 00:53:50,471
not just your composers, I mean the sound team too.

814
00:53:51,212 --> 00:53:52,592
Andrew put a lot of hours into the game,

815
00:53:52,612 --> 00:53:54,553
and Andrew and his team put a lot of hours into the game.

816
00:53:55,354 --> 00:53:56,775
And it really does make a difference.

817
00:53:56,975 --> 00:53:58,896
It is more work, but we're making games right,

818
00:53:58,916 --> 00:53:59,456
and it should be fun.

819
00:54:01,814 --> 00:54:02,674
This is just a little note.

820
00:54:03,575 --> 00:54:06,457
I said all of Auri's music was trigger-based.

821
00:54:06,777 --> 00:54:11,180
We didn't really have a BPM engine, and that's something I would have liked to have done

822
00:54:11,200 --> 00:54:12,841
because it made transitions really difficult.

823
00:54:14,702 --> 00:54:18,225
And lastly, getting on board really helped me and helped the team.

824
00:54:19,486 --> 00:54:25,790
And also having the amount of input and being able to give the amount of feedback.

825
00:54:26,490 --> 00:54:28,831
Makes me feel valued. And we all want to feel valued, right?

826
00:54:29,071 --> 00:54:30,352
When we're, when we're working on a game,

827
00:54:31,172 --> 00:54:32,872
we want our opinion to feel important.

828
00:54:33,012 --> 00:54:39,814
And when you are on early and you have a big say in the, in the development process,

829
00:54:40,295 --> 00:54:44,196
I don't feel like I'm just getting this list of stuff that I need to deliver.

830
00:54:44,316 --> 00:54:47,537
I really felt like I was able to help shape the experience.

831
00:54:47,577 --> 00:54:49,117
And I know Andrew felt the same way.

832
00:54:50,918 --> 00:54:53,301
So, just to conclude, testing and iteration is king.

833
00:54:53,781 --> 00:54:55,023
It takes time, but it's king.

834
00:54:55,584 --> 00:54:57,426
Do not underestimate the audio department.

835
00:54:57,626 --> 00:55:00,469
We're storytellers too, not just asset creators.

836
00:55:01,731 --> 00:55:06,156
And all the feedback is valuable, no matter how much you don't like it.

837
00:55:06,677 --> 00:55:07,838
Just a little quick example.

838
00:55:08,238 --> 00:55:09,240
One of our artists said to me...

839
00:55:09,940 --> 00:55:11,762
I don't like the piano in one of the cues.

840
00:55:11,802 --> 00:55:13,103
I'm like, what do you know?

841
00:55:13,203 --> 00:55:15,204
I know you don't play any musical instrument whatsoever.

842
00:55:15,244 --> 00:55:17,125
But actually, that person's feedback

843
00:55:17,246 --> 00:55:19,507
is valuable because they don't know about music.

844
00:55:19,988 --> 00:55:22,149
And I was like, well, it cost me 10 seconds

845
00:55:22,169 --> 00:55:24,471
to try it just to turning down the piano, and it was better.

846
00:55:25,531 --> 00:55:28,614
Sometimes the person who doesn't know about music is right, too.

847
00:55:30,622 --> 00:55:36,507
And Moon's thing about defining what the game is early on really helped us at the end, like

848
00:55:36,547 --> 00:55:37,628
when it came to crunch time.

849
00:55:38,489 --> 00:55:41,672
I've rushed the ending a little bit because I really want to open it up for questions.

850
00:55:41,712 --> 00:55:45,115
I know we've only got five minutes, but we are the last presentation, so hopefully they're

851
00:55:45,136 --> 00:55:46,116
going to let us stick around.

852
00:55:47,298 --> 00:55:49,380
Okay, so if you've got questions, line up.

853
00:55:49,920 --> 00:55:51,301
Otherwise, that's it from us.

854
00:56:03,267 --> 00:56:03,768
All right, go for it.

