00:56:04,510 --> 00:56:05,774
I was wondering if you could tell us

856
00:56:06,416 --> 00:56:09,685
something about the process of implementation of the audio.

857
00:56:11,201 --> 00:56:12,341
Sound, music, or both?

858
00:56:14,103 --> 00:56:15,124
If you're able, both?

859
00:56:15,824 --> 00:56:17,185
Andrew, you probably best.

860
00:56:17,205 --> 00:56:19,527
We were fully integrated with the tools,

861
00:56:19,647 --> 00:56:22,249
and we were getting builds on a minute basis,

862
00:56:22,269 --> 00:56:25,512
getting data in the tool, implementing.

863
00:56:26,412 --> 00:56:31,376
But as we said, we were using stock Unity engine.

864
00:56:31,676 --> 00:56:33,318
So it was that.

865
00:56:35,099 --> 00:56:37,221
Anything specific you want to ask about?

866
00:56:39,352 --> 00:56:45,336
Well, how fast were you able to implement it in the game and share it with the whole team?

867
00:56:45,396 --> 00:56:45,896
Instantly.

868
00:56:46,097 --> 00:56:47,057
Instantly, yeah.

869
00:56:47,297 --> 00:56:50,740
So, I would just drag it onto our Mii's Tortoise SDN and...

870
00:56:54,278 --> 00:56:59,360
We, we, uh, I would just drag and drop WAV files, update within like 15 seconds, upload,

871
00:56:59,900 --> 00:57:02,980
get a good internet connection if you're doing distributed development, it's really important.

872
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:08,361
Um, but, uh, yeah, I could get feedback within like 10 minutes if I wanted to.

873
00:57:08,381 --> 00:57:09,042
Um.

874
00:57:09,242 --> 00:57:09,822
Yeah, that's true.

875
00:57:09,982 --> 00:57:15,463
I mean, it was, you would get feedback within 20 minutes, 10, 20 minutes if, um, you put

876
00:57:15,503 --> 00:57:16,703
something on the Skype chat.

877
00:57:17,643 --> 00:57:17,883
Thank you.

878
00:57:19,830 --> 00:57:21,772
Hi, thanks so much. My question's for Gareth.

879
00:57:22,733 --> 00:57:27,076
I was hoping you could talk some about your musical inspirations.

880
00:57:27,337 --> 00:57:33,422
How much for this specific score, inspiration from other composers affected you?

881
00:57:33,762 --> 00:57:34,583
Kind of how that worked.

882
00:57:34,843 --> 00:57:37,365
It's less about, for me it's less about other composers.

883
00:57:37,385 --> 00:57:42,149
I think one of the dangers when, are you a student or are you...

884
00:57:42,209 --> 00:57:42,629
I'm a student.

885
00:57:42,709 --> 00:57:45,732
Okay, right. So, stop listening to soundtracks.

886
00:57:47,451 --> 00:57:51,615
If you like the Ori soundtrack, that's great, but when you're doing your own work, stop

887
00:57:51,675 --> 00:57:55,798
listening to soundtracks, because they've been influenced by temp music too, and the

888
00:57:55,878 --> 00:58:00,342
best thing you can do is find some weird stuff from all over the world, because that's the

889
00:58:00,382 --> 00:58:02,423
stuff that's going to make your work unique.

890
00:58:02,744 --> 00:58:06,327
Now, once you've done that, then you can go back and listen to some soundtracks.

891
00:58:07,628 --> 00:58:12,812
So I lived in Japan for three years, and I got to travel around Asia a lot.

892
00:58:15,134 --> 00:58:16,595
that's a real musical treat.

893
00:58:16,915 --> 00:58:19,297
Like, there's just a bunch of instruments I'd never even heard of.

894
00:58:19,357 --> 00:58:20,378
I, like, look at them and I'm like,

895
00:58:20,698 --> 00:58:21,719
you can make a sound with that?

896
00:58:22,419 --> 00:58:24,961
And I was like, OK, well, I'm going to remember this

897
00:58:25,021 --> 00:58:26,563
and store it in the memory bank for the future

898
00:58:26,583 --> 00:58:29,285
when I have a chance to do a project which might benefit from it.

899
00:58:30,846 --> 00:58:33,508
And so, once I'd done that,

900
00:58:33,748 --> 00:58:35,489
then, to answer your question,

901
00:58:36,310 --> 00:58:39,072
you're tying in the weird and wonderful stuff.

902
00:58:39,792 --> 00:58:43,115
And for Ori, Thomas Newman's pretty clearly an influence.

903
00:58:44,977 --> 00:58:47,979
And one of my favorite composers is Michael Danner,

904
00:58:48,259 --> 00:58:49,680
especially his score for Life of Pi.

905
00:58:50,300 --> 00:58:51,321
I think it's a masterpiece.

906
00:58:51,801 --> 00:58:52,781
He did win the Oscar for it.

907
00:58:53,002 --> 00:58:55,563
And if you haven't heard the Life of Pi score,

908
00:58:55,623 --> 00:58:56,624
please go listen to it now.

909
00:58:56,704 --> 00:58:57,984
If you liked Ori's soundtrack, you

910
00:58:58,004 --> 00:58:59,525
will like the Life of Pi soundtrack.

911
00:59:00,005 --> 00:59:01,066
So I hope that answers your question.

912
00:59:01,226 --> 00:59:02,086
Yeah, thank you so much.

913
00:59:02,106 --> 00:59:04,848
Hi, guys.

914
00:59:05,388 --> 00:59:06,749
So the game's freaking amazing.

915
00:59:07,930 --> 00:59:08,210
Thank you.

916
00:59:08,270 --> 00:59:09,250
The music is beautiful.

917
00:59:09,611 --> 00:59:10,831
The sound is perfect.

918
00:59:13,028 --> 00:59:16,871
team. Sounds like it was a really awesome team to work with and I'm curious if at any

919
00:59:16,971 --> 00:59:18,392
point it felt like work.

920
00:59:20,033 --> 00:59:25,898
Oh yeah, I mean, there was, yeah, I mean it's, it was, uh.

921
00:59:27,936 --> 00:59:31,677
Let me first say that I have a love affair with that game.

922
00:59:31,777 --> 00:59:37,559
And it's deeply personal, as much as it is a great career

923
00:59:37,979 --> 00:59:38,499
project.

924
00:59:40,159 --> 00:59:43,660
But the struggle is real, man.

925
00:59:43,740 --> 00:59:44,040
I don't know.

926
00:59:46,881 --> 00:59:48,642
Development is hard, making games is hard.

927
00:59:49,263 --> 00:59:52,705
And when you're, especially when you're in the indie world,

928
00:59:52,785 --> 00:59:54,926
you don't have a lot of the cushy environments that,

929
00:59:54,966 --> 01:00:00,249
you know, and the established modes of creating

930
01:00:01,610 --> 01:00:04,832
or structuring a project in which you can get comfortable

931
01:00:05,392 --> 01:00:09,074
and have some level of prediction or understanding

932
01:00:09,114 --> 01:00:10,455
about what your future looks like.

933
01:00:10,935 --> 01:00:15,597
This game was developed without a future. I mean, really, without knowing what the next month was,

934
01:00:15,657 --> 01:00:21,518
and that's through four and a half years of development. To give one example, this game

935
01:00:21,559 --> 01:00:26,740
was supposed to be, and had been talked about, and had been developed to be a three-hour experience,

936
01:00:26,840 --> 01:00:33,862
all the way up until E3, prior to the year of releasing it. So we tripled the scope of the game

937
01:00:34,282 --> 01:00:35,623
at some point with...

938
01:00:36,852 --> 01:00:40,035
at that time, 6 months left in the schedule.

939
01:00:40,655 --> 01:00:42,937
Now, I've been around the block a little bit,

